&lt;P&gt;&lt;STRONG&gt;Ten tenets of lean manufacturing &lt;/STRONG&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P&gt;&lt;EM&gt;If your company wants to get lean, whatâs the best way to start? &lt;/EM&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P&gt;&lt;EM&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/EM&gt;&lt;STRONG&gt;&lt;EM&gt;Secure backing from the top &lt;/EM&gt;&lt;/STRONG&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P&gt;Before doing anything, get firm support from your companyâs decision-makers. âIf you are not Lean and want to get started, the top management team has to understand what theyâre getting into,â says TBMâs Sharma. Adds Emersonâs Hamby: âYou need a top-down approach, rather than a grass-roots effort.â &lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P&gt;&lt;STRONG&gt;&lt;EM&gt;Roll up your shirtsleeves &lt;/EM&gt;&lt;/STRONG&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P&gt;Lean can produce dramatic improvements. But no one said it would be easy. âMany people are looking for a quick answer to a difficult problem,â says Sharma. âThey donât hear that theyâll have to do some work first.â &lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P&gt;&lt;STRONG&gt;&lt;EM&gt;Communicate and educate &lt;/EM&gt;&lt;/STRONG&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P&gt;âWe spend a lot of time communicating before, during and at the end [of a Kaizan event, when a team scrutinizes operations and then makes suggestions for improvements] to make sure everyone understands,â says Pellaâs Van Zanten. âCommunication is key. When we have a success, we really communicate it.â Adds Emersonâs Stephen: âYou need a lot of education. Build awareness, train people and get some champions.â &lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P&gt;&lt;STRONG&gt;&lt;EM&gt;Donât skimp on training &lt;/EM&gt;&lt;/STRONG&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P&gt;Lean manufacturing goes against the grain of many manufacturing traditions. âLeave enough time to change the thinking within the company,â advises Parker. âTest and make sure there is a level of understanding. If [the staff doesnât] get it on the first round of training, do another round. Make sure you have the culture turned around before going forward.â Remember that Lean changes more than just production processes; it can affect everything from personnel performance measures to how salespeople promise delivery dates to customers. &lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P&gt;&lt;STRONG&gt;&lt;EM&gt;Apply suitable metrics &lt;/EM&gt;&lt;/STRONG&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P&gt;Re-jig how you measure success and failure. âUnder the old cost-accounting system, your score was good if your most expensive machine was running 24/7,â notes Parker. Lean canât succeed, he says, âif you donât change the way people keep score.â The traditional measures of success â efficiency and utilization â need to be replaced with agility, lead time, inventory turns and quality across the board. &lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P&gt;&lt;STRONG&gt;&lt;EM&gt;Help your partners &lt;/EM&gt;&lt;/STRONG&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P&gt;âIf you donât extend Lean beyond your four walls, you will have dissatisfied suppliers,â warns Oracleâs Modi. âCompanies that are far reaching have educated their suppliers on lean.â In fact, the most successful lean companies involve their suppliers in product design in order to improve quality and simplify manufacturing. And they work together to improve communication methods and shorten lead times throughout the supply chain. &lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P&gt;&lt;STRONG&gt;&lt;EM&gt;Think big &lt;/EM&gt;&lt;/STRONG&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P&gt;As a company shortens its production cycles, manufacturing experiments can be quick and painless. So an attempt to improve things can hold tremendous potential, and can be made without serious consequences â even if it fails. âWhen in doubt, be bold,â advises Van Zanten. âWe set aggressive goals. You canât just make minor tweaks.â &lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P&gt;&lt;STRONG&gt;&lt;EM&gt;Shift the goalposts &lt;/EM&gt;&lt;/STRONG&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P&gt;âDonât declare victory too soon,â recommends Sharma. Pellaâs Van Zanten likes to remember how after a year of lean efforts, the CIO asked him for a progress report. âAbout 25 percent,â Van Zanten estimated. A year later, the CIO asked the same question, yet this time the response was 10 percent. The anecdote shows that lean manufacturing is like getting a new pair of glasses that help you continually to see new ways in which to reduce waste and improve business. âThe more you do, the more opportunities there are that become visible,â adds Pellaâs Printz. &lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P&gt;&lt;STRONG&gt;&lt;EM&gt;Get the faith &lt;/EM&gt;&lt;/STRONG&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P&gt;âContinuous improvement (kaizen) is our way of life,â says industrial conglomerate Danaher, which has been a lean manufacturer since the 1980s. Only with focus and dedication can Lean/Six Sigma bring benefits to your company. âWe are finding that customers who have adopted lean as a religion are seeing bigger benefits,â says Modi. &lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P&gt;&lt;STRONG&gt;&lt;EM&gt;Prepare for the long haul &lt;/EM&gt;&lt;/STRONG&gt;&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;P&gt;Lean doesnât end after you reach your first set of goals, and itâs not a finite project with a beginning and end date. Rather itâs a way of business life that executives need to pursue continuously. âThereâs a vigilance that has to be maintained from the executive suite,â says Parker. âYouâre always looking for a better way,â adds Robert Azavedo, Oracleâs director of discrete manufacturing industries in Europe. âThe journey never ends.â &lt;/P&gt;
